Sunlight: partial sun

This specimen was found in a medical office landscape bed.  The stems were about 14" with shorter and longer stems on other plants nearby.  The stems are square with hard edges, the side of which are generously covered with downward pointing tiny stiff hairs that catch surfaces, allowing stems to creep out and up and over other stems, plants and surfaces from the tap root. 
Leaves are whorled (6-8 leaves in a whorl), and also covered with downward pointing hairs. Whorls are well spaced on the stems. Very small, four-part, white flowers form on the tips of short branches that start from the junction of leaf and stem.

Calflora considers this particular species a CA native.

Flowers were not fully open and may have closed because the weather was cloudy and it had recently rained. They were a peachy orange or salmon color.  5-petals that overlap at the base. Flower are on slender stalks, and grow singly between the stem and leaf stalks.

Leaves are well-spaced on the stem, opposite and stalkless. 
They take an oval shape - wider at the stem attachment end and pointed at the tip. Leaves have a hairy underside with dark spots.

I originally learned this plant/flower as "poor man's weather glass" - so named because of the opening and closing of the flowers.

description: A bit rusty on ID, but believe this is a juvenile Aneides lugubris. Found it sheltered under garden boots after rain. Four toes front, five toes rear. Toes and feet slender, no prominent webbing. Relatively triangular head. Counted ~14 costal folds.TL (snout to end of tail) ~2"(5cm). Not easy to see in photos but has blotchy appearance in addition to iridescent yellowish spots. Once it warmed in my wet hand, it began to climb up my torso with agility. Openned and closed mouth repeatedly as it began to climb. (Possible defensive posture.) After animal calmed, placed in a nearby dark wet location.
